{"Category": "Arts", "End Date": "", "Name": "Art Exhibit: Tour with Collector Charles Derby", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/art-exhibit-tour-collector", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "6:00-8:00pm", "Date": "Thu, Mar 1, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Collector Charles Derby will offer a tour of the exhibition '5 Takes on African Art / 42 Paintings' by Fred Wilson with personal anecdotes about his forty years of collecting and acquiring the objects on display in this exhibition. In conjunction with Amherst Arts Night Plus."},
{"Category": "History, Language, Humanities, Global Studies", "End Date": "", "Name": "Lecture: \"Compound Discomfort, Episodic Puzzlement\" by Kenneth Mills", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/lecture-compound-discomfort", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "4:00 PM", "Date": "Thu, Mar 1, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "In this lecture apart of the Colonial Latin America Lecture Series, Kenneth Mills will draw from a book he is writing about on the transatlantic journey of a Castilian Hieronymite alms-gatherer and image-maker named Diego de Oca\u00f1a (ca. 1570-1608). The lecture will focus upon Oca\u00f1a's fragmentarily reported and partly invented episodes, with particular attention to the portrayal of culturally composite people, places and phenomena. Discussion will follow the lecture.\n\nKenneth Mills (D. Phil. Oxon 1992) is J. Frederick Hoffman Professor of History at the University of Michigan. He has taught at Oxford, Liverpool, Princeton and Toronto.\n\nCo-Sponsors:  \n\nSpanish Department, Amherst College; Latin American and Latino/a Studies, Smith College;\n\nUMass: CLACLS; Department of Languages, Literatures, and Cultures; Department of History; Spanish and Portuguese Program; Comparative Literature Program"},
{"Category": "Social Justice, Gender Studies, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "Lecture: 'Specialization, Power, and Inequality'", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/lecture-specialization-power", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "4:00 PM", "Date": "Thu, Mar 1, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Please join the economics department for the 3rd Annual Samuel Bowles Lecture to be presented by professor Emerita Nancy Folbre. \n\nIn this lecture titled 'Specialization, Power, and Inequality: The Case of the Care Penalty', Folbre will discuss several distinctive features of care provision that weaken the links between value created and rewards paid, and how, as a result, care providers (predominantly women) find themselves in a weak economic position. Reception to follow."},
{"Category": "Literature, Arts, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "Author Talk: Andrea Hairston", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/author-talk-andrea-hairston", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "5:00-7:00pm", "Date": "Thu, Mar 1, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Andrea Hairston will be reading sections from her new novel, \"Will Do Magic for Small Change\" and musical dynamo Pan Morigan will sing songs she has written based on lyrics from the book. The melodies are influenced by Pan\u2019s research into the banjo and blues, Irish music and something indefinable.\n\nHairston is the Louise Wolff Kahn 1931 Professor of Theatre and Afro-American Studies at Smith College, is an award-winning playwright, novelist and essayist whose works have appeared on stage, television and radio. She serves as the artistic director of the Chrysalis Theatre, where her science fiction plays are produced."},
{"Category": "History, Humanities, Arts, Global Studies", "End Date": "", "Name": "Lecture: 'The Modern and the (Dis-)Locations of Architectural History'", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/lecture-modern-and-dis", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "6:00 PM", "Date": "Thu, Mar 1, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Mark Jarzombek discusses how architectural history in the last decades has risen to the level of the geo- political. \n\nThis transformation had a lot to do with the emergence the post-WWII and post- Cold War nation state and was facilitated by UNESCO, the museum-boom beginning in the 1980s and the tourist industry. The result is an emerging tension between architectural history as an academic discipline and architectural history as part of a construction of local populist imaginaries. One of the results of this transformation is that though we supposedly live in a global age, the possibility of writing a global history of architecture is ever more elusive."},
{"Category": "Literature, Arts, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "Tell Us What You Think with Parul Sehgal & Christopher Benfey", "URL": "https://www.amherst.edu/news/calendar/node/701230", "Location": "Amherst College, Amherst, MA", "Time": "11:00am-12:00pm", "Date": "Fri, Mar 2, 2018", "Organization": "Amherst College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "As part of Amherst College LitFest 2018, Professor and award-winning author Judith Frank hosts a conversation, \u201cTell Us What You Think: The Pleasures and Perils of Writing about Books,\u201d with Parul Sehgal, New York Times book critic, and Christopher Benfey, author, journalist and professor of English at Mount Holyoke College.\n\nThis event is free, open to the public and will be followed by Q&A. Light lunch served.\n\nVisit www.amherst.edu/go/litfest to see the LitFest 2018 festival schedule and biographies of each guest."},
{"Category": "Literature, Arts, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "An Evening with Junot D\u00edaz", "URL": "https://www.amherst.edu/news/calendar/node/701231", "Location": "Amherst College, Amherst, MA", "Time": "7:30-9:00pm", "Date": "Fri, Mar 2, 2018", "Organization": "Amherst College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "X", "Description": "As part of Amherst College LitFest 2018, Pulitzer Prize-winning author Junot D\u00edaz will give a reading followed by a conversation with Jennifer Acker '00, editor-in-chief of The Common literary magazine.\n\nThis event will be followed by a Q&A and book signing. It is free and open to the public.\n\n*Please note: The venue for this event is Johnson Chapel, which seats 600 people. We recommend arriving early to get a seat. In the event that the venue is full, we will provide seating and a video feed (for on-campus visitors only) in Stirn Auditorium.\n\nVisit www.amherst.edu/go/litfest to see the LitFest 2018 festival schedule and biographies of each guest."},
{"Category": "Science, Sustainability, Social Justice", "End Date": "", "Name": "Our Living Building Tour Program", "URL": "http://www.hitchcockcenter.org/programs/community-programs/#sustainability", "Location": "Hampshire College, Amherst, MA", "Time": "4:00 PM", "Date": "Fri, Mar 2, 2018", "Organization": "Hitchcock Center for the Environment", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Come meet our newest educator \u2013 our building! It is designed to model systems in nature, it is net zero energy, net zero water, has composting toilets, and has been made with responsibly sourced non-toxic materials, come check it out at one of our bi-monthly tours. Tours typically last from 1-1.5 hours. Note: We are pleased to be able to offer Spanish language translators for our building tours. If you or someone you know could benefit from translation, please let us know in advance, so that we may schedule a translator for your tour date."},
