{"Category": "Literature, Arts, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "Reading: Melih Levi \u201815 and Lindsay Stern \u201813", "URL": "https://www.amherst.edu/academiclife/departments/cwc/events", "Location": "Amherst, MA", "Time": "8:00 PM", "Date": "Wed, Mar 28, 2018", "Organization": "Amherst College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Originally from Istanbul, Turkey, Melih Levi studied English at Amherst College. His co-translation of one of the first Turkish novels, Fel\u00e2tun Bey and R\u00e2k\u0131m Efendi, was published by Syracuse University Press in 2016, and his recent projects include translating short stories by the Turkish writer Tezer \u00d6zl\u00fc. He is currently a PhD student in Comparative Literature at Stanford University, where he is studying modernist poetry.\n\nLindsay Stern is the author of two novellas, Town of Shadows and L\u00fcz, and a novel, Better Animals, forthcoming from Viking. After graduating from Amherst, she taught and wrote in Cambodia, India, South Africa, and Peru on a Watson Fellowship. Since then, she has received numerous literary awards and completed her MFA in fiction at the Iowa Writers\u2019 Workshop in 2017. She is currently pursuing a PhD in Comparative Literature at Yale University."},
{"Category": "History, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "\u201cDepicting Justice Through Fiction in a Western Massachusetts Setting\u201d", "URL": "https://pvhn.wordpress.com/event-calenda/", "Location": "Springfield, MA", "Time": "12:15 PM", "Date": "Thu, Mar 29, 2018", "Organization": "Springfield Museums", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Michael A. Ponser, novelist and Senior Judge, U.S. District Court"},
{"Category": "Literature, Humanities, Arts", "End Date": "", "Name": "Visiting Writers Series: Colin Barrett", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/visiting-writers-series-colin", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "8:00 PM", "Date": "Thu, Mar 29, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Colin Barrett's debut collection of short stories, Young Skins, was published in September 2013 by the independent Irish publisher Stinging Fly Press. It was subsequently picked up by Jonathan Cape in the UK and Black Cat Editions, an imprint of Grove Atlantic, in the US.\n\nIt received three major literary prizes in 2014, including The Guardian First Book Award, The Frank O'Connor International Short Story prize, and the Rooney Prize for Irish Literature. It has so far been translated into 6 languages, with Japanese and Chinese editions forthcoming in 2018. In 2015 Colin was one of the selected honorees of the 5 under 35 National Book Awards in the US. His stories have appeared in The New Yorker, Granta Magazine, The New Statesman and other literary journals."},
{"Category": "Diversity/Equity/Inclusion, Social Justice", "End Date": "", "Name": "Sami Schalk Lecture", "URL": "https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/new-calendar?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D266936190", "Location": "Smith College, Northampton, MA", "Time": "7:00-9:30pm", "Date": "Fri, Mar 30, 2018", "Organization": "Smith College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "As part of the 5-college Disability Studies conference, Sami Schalk will give a talk and lecture from her new book, \"Bodyminds Reimagined: (Dis)ability, Race, and Gender in Black Women's Speculative Fiction\""},
{"Category": "Arts, History, Humanities, Literature, Gender Studies, Social Justice, Diversity/Equity/Inclusion, Global Studies", "End Date": "", "Name": "Book Salon with Laura Furlan on Indigenous Cities: Urban Indian Fiction and the Histories of Relocation", "URL": "https://www.fivecolleges.edu/fcwsrc/events", "Location": "Mount Holyoke College, South Hadley, MA ", "Time": "6:00-8:00pm", "Date": "Mon, Apr 2, 2018", "Organization": "Mount Holyoke College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Join us for a discussion of Indigenous Cities: Urban Indian Fiction and the Histories of Relocation (University of Nebraska Press) by Laura Furlan (Assistant Professor of English, UMass Amherst).\n\nIn Indigenous Cities Laura Furlan demonstrates that stories of the urban experience are essential to an understanding of modern Indigeneity. She situates Native identity among theories of diaspora, cosmopolitanism, and transnationalism by examining urban narratives\u2014such as those written by Sherman Alexie, Janet Campbell Hale, Louise Erdrich, and Susan Power\u2014along with the work of filmmakers and artists. In these stories Native peoples navigate new surroundings, find and reformulate community, and maintain and redefine Indian identity in the postrelocation era. These narratives illuminate the changing relationship between urban Indigenous peoples and their tribal nations and territories and the ways in which new cosmopolitan bonds both reshape and are interpreted by tribal identities.\n\nDiscussants: Christine DeLucia (Assistant Professor of History, Mount Holyoke College), Laura Doyle (Professor of English, UMass Amherst), Laura Fugikawa (Visiting Assistant Professor in the Study of Women and Gender and English Language and Literatures, Smith College), and Kiara Vigil (Assistant Professor of American Studies, Amherst College)"},
{"Category": "Humanities, Literature, Arts, Featured", "End Date": "", "Name": "Five College PoetryFest", "URL": "https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/new-calendar?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D266600759", "Location": "Smith College, Northampton, MA", "Time": "7:30-9:00pm", "Date": "Tue, Apr 3, 2018", "Organization": "Smith College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "The 16th Annual Reading in celebration of poetry at Amherst, Hampshire, Mount Holyoke, and Smith Colleges and the University of Massachusetts, featuring two students from each institution: Jonah Davis and Avery Farmer (Amherst); Lazuli Liu and Corrie Owens-Beauchesne (Hampshire); Bennett Sambrook and Becca Mullen (Mt. Holyoke); Janelle Tan and Savannah Tilley (Smith); Stacey Cusson and Cressida Richards (UMass)"},
{"Category": "History, Humanities, Global Studies", "End Date": "", "Name": "Bianca Murillo Lecture: \"Market Encounters: Consumer Cultures in Twentieth-Century Ghana\"", "URL": "https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/new-calendar?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D280375078", "Location": "Smith College, Northampton, MA", "Time": "5:00-6:30pm", "Date": "Tue, Apr 3, 2018", "Organization": "", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "A public lecture by Professor Bianca Murillo, Associate Professor of History, California State University, Dominguez Hills.  It is related to her recent book, Market Encounters: Consumer Cultures in Twentieth-Century Ghana.  The talk will focus on the changing nature of consumer culture in twentieth-century Ghanaian history, namely in terms of the ways in which Ghanaians created new cultural, social, and political meanings out of what the items they bought and sold. Sponsored by the Department of History."},
{"Category": "Health, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "Health Law Workshop ", "URL": "https://events.mtholyoke.edu/MasterCalendar/EventDetails.aspx?EventDetailId=49923", "Location": "Mount Holyoke College, South Hadley, MA ", "Time": "6:00-8:00pm", "Date": "Tue, Apr 3, 2018", "Organization": "Mount Holyoke College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Dr. Francis X. Shen, Harvard Law Senior Fellow, will present a workshop on healthcare and law."},
{"Category": "Arts, Literature, Featured", "End Date": "", "Name": "Word! Festival", "URL": "https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/new-calendar?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D275393735", "Location": "Smith College, Northampton, MA", "Time": "7:30-10:00pm", "Date": "Thu, Apr 5, 2018", "Organization": "Smith College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "X", "Description": "WORD! Festival\nThe annual WORD! Festival, now over 30 years old, will present staged readings of short poly-cultural plays (or excerpts of plays) by Five College students awarded the 2018 James Baldwin Playwriting Prize.\nFree and open to the public."},
{"Category": "Literature, Arts, Humanities", "End Date": "", "Name": "Edible Book Festival", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/edible-book-festival", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "12:00-4:00pm", "Date": "Thu, Apr 5, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "The UMass Amherst Libraries invite you to join us in celebrating this year's Edible Book Festival on April 5, 2018. This festival has been celebrated internationally on or around April 1 since 2000 in commemoration of the birthday of gastronome and author Jean-Anthelme Brillat-Savarin. All members of the UMass Amherst community are invited to submit edible book-inspired creations which will then be displayed, judged, and eaten!\n\nEntry Rules\n\nEach entry should depict a literary work (fiction or nonfiction) or a literary character.  Puns on titles are especially encouraged!\nEntries should not require refrigeration.\nEntries must be mostly edible (occasional non-edible props permitted).\nEntries should be no larger than 12\"x 16\".\nBy entering the competition, you are granting permission for UMass Libraries to photograph your entry with the possibility of including it on our website, in our newsletter, or in ScholarWorks. \nPrizes will be given for Best in Show, Most Creative, and Best Pun"},
{"Category": "Literature, Humanities, Arts", "End Date": "", "Name": "Visiting Writers Series: Sarah Ladipo Manyika", "URL": "http://www.umass.edu/events/visiting-writers-series-sarah", "Location": "Umass Amherst, Amherst, MA", "Time": "8:00 PM", "Date": "Fri, Apr 6, 2018", "Organization": "Umass Amherst", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Novelist and essayist Sarah Ladipo Manyika was raised in Nigeria and has lived in Kenya, France and England.\n\nShe has a doctorate from the University of California, Berkeley. Her second novel, Like a Mule Bringing Ice Cream to the Sun (2016), has been described as \"gorgeous and finely crafted\u2026. [It] shows ordinary people at their best.\"\n\nNoting the paucity of stories about older women who have lived colorful lives, especially African women, Manyika says, \u201cWhen I cannot find stories that I\u2019d like to read, I try writing them for myself.\u201d She is currently books editor at ozy.com."},
{"Category": "Gender Studies, Diversity/Equity/Inclusion, Social Justice, Leadership", "End Date": "", "Name": "Women of Color Trailblazers Leadership Conference 2018 ", "URL": "https://events.mtholyoke.edu/MasterCalendar/EventDetails.aspx?EventDetailId=49410", "Location": "Mount Holyoke College, South Hadley, MA ", "Time": "9:00am-7:00pm", "Date": "Sat, Apr 7, 2018", "Organization": "Mount Holyoke College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "The conference theme is \"Empowerment through Engagement.\" Keynote speakers are Tamika Mallory, Carmen Perez, and Linda Sarsour, founders of the National Women's March. The keynote address is free and open to the public."},
{"Category": "Arts", "End Date": "", "Name": "Sightlines Tour: Private Lives in the Public Eye", "URL": "https://events.mtholyoke.edu/MasterCalendar/EventDetails.aspx?EventDetailId=49649", "Location": "Mount Holyoke College, South Hadley, MA ", "Time": "1:30-2:15pm", "Date": "Sat, Apr 7, 2018", "Organization": "Mount Holyoke College Art Museum", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Visitors on this tour, led by Rachel Kim \u201921, Student Guide, will uncover questions about the private versus the public self. How do we, as individuals, select and neglect parts of our identities for display? How do the private lives of famous figures compare to their public images? What are the implications of commemoration? Together we will explore the relationship of museums \u2014 as public institutions \u2014 to the intimate, personal works they exhibit.\n\nFree and open to the public.  "},
{"Category": "Humanities, History", "End Date": "", "Name": "Kahn Institute lecture: Perry Anderson", "URL": "https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/new-calendar?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D277465020", "Location": "Smith College, Northampton, MA", "Time": "5:00-6:30pm", "Date": "Mon, Apr 9, 2018", "Organization": "Smith College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Perry Anderson, British historian and political essayist and author of Passages from Antiquity to Feudalism and many other writings, will deliver a public lecture in conjunction with the Kahn Institute project on War."},
